SIMPLE: fatality
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fatality
<hw>Fa*tal"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;<plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Fatalities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>fatalitas</ets>:
cf. F. <ets>fatalit⟦eacute⟧</ets>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of
being fatal, or proceeding from destiny; invincible necessity, superior
to, and independent of, free and rational control.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Stoics held a <qex>fatality</qex>, and a fixed, unalterable
course of events.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being fatal; tendency to destruction or
danger, as if by decree of fate; mortaility.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The year sixty-three is conceived to carry with it the most
considerable <qex>fatality</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ser T.
Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By a strange <qex>fatality</qex> men suffer their dissenting.</q>
<rj><qau>Eikon Basilike.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is decreed by fate or which is fatal; a
fatal event.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fatally</ent>⟦br⟧
